This gun was recently purchased directly from the family of Daniel Waters in Massachusetts and has never previously been offered for sale. Daniel Austin Waters was born in 1840 and resided in Lowell, Massachusetts. At the outbreak of the Civil War on April 12th, 1861, Waters was working as a clerk for Burbank Chase & Co., a clothing store in Lowell. Almost immediately an independent infantry company was organized in Lowell called "Richardson's Light Infantry". Waters enlisted with the unit as a private on May 21st, 1861. Apparently Daniel Waters was well favored by his female co-workers as the ladies of Burbank Chase & Co. pitched in together and purchased him a brand new 1849 Colt revolver which was presented to him as a going away gift. title: For Sale:  Nice Egyptian Belgian FNH SAFN-49 8mm Mauser Rifle
postcontent: Up for auction is an Egyptian contract FN SAFN49 rifle, chambered for the classic and available 8mm Mauser (7.92x57mm) round. This rifle is in VG+ condition, and is complete with all of its parts. It is C&R and comes with a period correct leather sling.After World War II, Fabrique Nationale de Herstal of Belgium introduced a then very modern self-loading military battle rifle. Designated as the SAFN or FN49, over 175,000 were produced during the 1950s; the majority in .30-06. It operated using a tilting bolt system and short stroke gas piston. These features FNH would later carry over to its hugely successful FAL series. This is why some call the FN49 the Father to the FAL.The rifle up for auction here was originally part of the Egyptian contract, which was made up of roughly 38,000 rifles in total. It fires 8mm Mauser, has a full length 23" barrel, parkerized finish on the metal, wooden furniture, and Arabic writing on several parts. It features a threaded barrel with muzzle nut, bayonet lug (takes most standard Mauser type bayonets) windage and elevation adjustable rear sights, and a fixed 10 round box magazine. Also somewhat uniquely, it has a small sliding dustcover to protect the action from dust and dirt, and a cocked action indicator at the front of the trigger guard. It uses a simple and effective thumb safety too. It has the Egyptian Eagle crest on its receiver, and the side is rollmarked Fabrique Nationale de Herstal.Rifle is in overall VG+ condition. It has a nice even finish, without any rust or real pitting visible. The bore is nice, with strong rifling and still pretty shiny; not at all shot out. The stock is smooth and is basically new. It has finger grooves and a plastic buttplate, so it is one of the replacement stocks put on by the importer. I believe these were made in Italy? Either way it is a nice looking and solid feeling stock.Mechanically, everything seems to work 100%. The bolt cycles, the trigger releases the hammer, the safety blocks the hammer, the magazine has a good spring and holds the bolt back when empty as it should, the dustcover slides as it should, the rear sight adjusts, and the gas valve rotates easily so it isn't stuck/rusted in place. So everything appears in good order here.  In summary rifle is i excellent condition. Shipping Available

title: For Sale:  COLT 1911 USMC 1914, SEMI AUTO PISTOL FOR SALE
postcontent: This is a scarce USMC contract pistol that was 1 of 500 pistols shipped to the U.S. Marine Corps Depot Quartermaster in Philadelphia, PA.Well i will have to give a rather brief description on this Lovely Gun: These were manufactured as a standard Army contract pistol and are distinguishable only by the serial number ranges. They all exhibit the early Colt parts and markings as follows; the left side of the frame has the small "UNITED STATES PROPERTY". Directly above the magazine catch release button is marked with the circled intertwined "WGP" of Major Walter G. Penfield the US Ordnance inspector at Colt. The right side frame is marked with the serial number and the top of the frame has the early acceptance proofs of the letter "H" and "T". The left side of the slide is marked with the very early Colt two-line patent/ address markings of "PATENTED APR 20 1897/SEPT. 9 1902, DEC 19 1905, FEB 14,1911",and "COLT'S PT. F.A. MFG CO./HARTFORD. CT. U.S.A." with the Rampant Colt behind the serrations. It also has the early round top rear sight and narrow front sight. The various parts and components are all the early versions such as; blue Colt barrel with the single "P and H" on top, early 1911 checkered slide stop, thin thumb piece, short grip safety, flat mainspring housing and the early short Colt hammer with the wide checkered spur. Two tone magazine with lanyard ring on the base and fitted with checkered walnut grips with a diamond around the screws and lanyard ring on the heel. But we must remember as these Colts 103 years old where disassembled for cleaning , many parts were picked up my mistake during reassembly serial Number: 84109, this was the third contract in 1914. The pistol shows mostly an artificial dark plum brown finish on the slide and frame with light wear through turning a gray patina on the front edges of the slide and the front grip strap. Condition 100% original parts ,with 50-60% finish , The grips are very good with a few minor dings and wear, and very crisp checkering. Most of these USMC 1911's saw heavy use and went through many rebuilds. very few Marine Corps 1911’s remain as most were lost in battle during WWI,the Banna wars and WWII To find one in any condition is difficult .All FFL fees apply when required, C&R License accepted Colt letter included. I have been told the stain marking on this Colt is caused by human blood, source crime lab. Serious Interested Buyer Only should contact me via email and or Text me on (352)388-7675

postcontent: This is a scarce USMC contract pistol that was 1 of 500 pistols shipped to the U.S. Marine Corps Depot Quartermaster in Philadelphia, PA.Well i will have to give a rather brief description on this Lovely Gun: These were manufactured as a standard Army contract pistol and are distinguishable only by the serial number ranges. They all exhibit the early Colt parts and markings as follows; the left side of the frame has the small "UNITED STATES PROPERTY". Directly above the magazine catch release button is marked with the circled intertwined "WGP" of Major Walter G. Penfield the US Ordnance inspector at Colt. The right side frame is marked with the serial number and the top of the frame has the early acceptance proofs of the letter "H" and "T". The left side of the slide is marked with the very early Colt two-line patent/ address markings of "PATENTED APR 20 1897/SEPT. 9 1902, DEC 19 1905, FEB 14,1911",and "COLT'S PT. F.A. MFG CO./HARTFORD. CT. U.S.A." with the Rampant Colt behind the serrations. It also has the early round top rear sight and narrow front sight. The various parts and components are all the early versions such as; blue Colt barrel with the single "P and H" on top, early 1911 checkered slide stop, thin thumb piece, short grip safety, flat mainspring housing and the early short Colt hammer with the wide checkered spur. Two tone magazine with lanyard ring on the base and fitted with checkered walnut grips with a diamond around the screws and lanyard ring on the heel. But we must remember as these Colts 103 years old where disassembled for cleaning , many parts were picked up my mistake during reassembly serial Number: 84109, this was the third contract in 1914. The pistol shows mostly an artificial dark plum brown finish on the slide and frame with light wear through turning a gray patina on the front edges of the slide and the front grip strap. Condition 100% original parts ,with 50-60% finish , The grips are very good with a few minor dings and wear, and very crisp checkering. Most of these USMC 1911's saw heavy use and went through many rebuilds. very few Marine Corps 1911’s remain as most were lost in battle during WWI,the Banna wars and WWII To find one in any condition is difficult .All FFL fees apply when required, C&R License accepted Colt letter included. I have been told the stain marking on this Colt is caused by human blood, source crime lab. Serious Interested Buyer Only should contact me via email and or Text me on (352)388-7675

title: For Sale:  Walther P5 Compact 9mm
postcontent: Walther P5 Compact. Chambered in 9mm, The Walther P5 Compact is the shorter and lighter version of the full-size P5. The Walther P5 Compact is a recoil-operated, locked-breech, 9 mm semi-automatic pistol. It utilizes the same design principles as the Walther P38 pistol of World War II fame. the P5 was a more in depth version of the famous Walther P38 and P1 series. Development on the P5 resulted in requests by German police and federal agencies for a new sidearm. Walther engineers decided to use the P1 model as the basis of the P5 and gave it a similar locking system, reinforced frame, and dual recoil springs. In addition, the Walther improved the extractor, shortened the barrel, and increased the slide length. The trigger is a standard double-action/single-action trigger. The slide lock also doubles as the decocker and is located on the left side of the frame. engaging it once will release the slide, a second time will drop the hammer without firing the gun. The Walther P5 Compact is used and comes with original box and papers, two magazines, and the gun comes with the original test target. No trades but will ship

title: For Sale:  Colt Python 357 John Wayne "McQ" Movie (Real) Gun
postcontent: Colt Python 357 With Super Rare 2&1/2" Barrel Movie Prop for John Wayne as Detective in the movie "McQ This gun was one of several used by John Wayne in the production of the movie "McQ". During filming, the Seattle Police Department officer assigned to the Department's Industrial Relations Division responsible for coordination between the Department and Batjac Productions became acquainted with the Duke. They met socially on several occasions and had many interactions during the shoot. At the end of the shoot, the Duke presented this gun to that police officer, Vince. It was eventually handed down to another family member who is the owner of this consignment. Shown in the photo is the Duke with members of the Seattle PD used as extras in the movie and Officer Vince (in civilian clothes). The photo is also stamped on the back by the official photographer. Also included is the Colt factory letter showing the gun shipped to the Salton Sea Armament Company in 1968. The Salton Sea Armament Company is the Dealer that provided real firearm props to the production company. Included in the photos of this item is a screen shot of John Wayne retrieving the Colt from his trunk, the Colt is seen a few other times as well in the movie "McQ."As far as the firearm goes, it is in excellent shape with only a few very minor marks from handling. The photos show a good depiction of overall condition and only a very small mark is seen on the cylinder. It can be fired and is about 99%. No box included as the movie actors usually threw them away.
